{"type":"message","id":"a39564ee","parentId":"c7c85ab1","timestamp":"2026-04-14T09:45:23.792Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The tts agent has its own workspace with its own memory files. This is a problem - it's isolated from the main workspace's memory.\n\nThe product-selector agent now has `spawnMode: \"session\"` and `workspaceDir: \"/home/halei/.openclaw/workspace\"` - this is the correct shared workspace.\n\nThe tts agent has its own workspace at `/home/halei/.openclaw/workspace-selector` with its own memory files. This means it doesn't share memory with the main agent.\n\nLet me think about what HALEI actually wants. They want all agents to share the same memory. The main workspace is `~/.openclaw/workspace`. \n\n\nFor product-selector, I've already set it to use the shared workspace with session mode enabled, so that's good to go. For the tts agent, I need to decide whether to consolidate it into the main workspace or keep it separate but ensure it can still access the shared memory layer. The issue is that `memory_search` relies on file paths, so if tts has its own workspace, it won't find the main workspace's memory files. I need to understand how OpenClaw's memory_search actually works to determine whether it queries a global store or something workspace-local. The cleanest approach would be to either migrate tts to use the shared workspace or reconfigure memory_search to point to a centralized location, but first I should verify which memory backends are actually being used and where the vector store is located."},{"type":"text","text":"`tts` 选品专家已经是 session 模式，但**工作区隔离**在 `workspace-selector`，有自己独立的 memory 文件——所以查不到主工作区的记忆。\n\n需要把它统一到主 workspace。有两个问题要确认：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_xewxqcvt8kx5_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls /home/halei/.openclaw/workspace-selector/memory/ 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"outpu