{"type":"message","id":"a54516b9","parentId":"7d8bae1e","timestamp":"2026-04-14T10:05:20.541Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the issue. The skills are installed in two places:\n1. `~/.openclaw/workspace/Selector/skills/` - has linkfox-echotik skills (but these seem to be ACP skills, not the agent skills)\n2. `~/.openclaw/workspace/.agents/skills/` - has 1688-product-search, 1688-ranking, alphashop-sel-product-search, google-trends\n\nThe `.agents/skills/` path is the active skills that the agent can use. The linkfox ones in `Selector/skills/` might not be registered.\n\nThe tts agent's tools allowlist is: `cron, read, write, edit, apply_patch, memory_search, memory_get, browser, message` - it does NOT include `exec`, `web_search`, `web_fetch`, or the skill-specific tools.\n \nThe core blocker is that tts agent can't run exec commands, which means it can't access the skill scripts that require shell access. I need to figure out whether the skills in `.agents/skills/` are registered as tools that should be automatically available, or if they need exec permissions to function at all. The real issue is that the tool allowlist doesn't include `exec`, which blocks skills from running their scripts. But I'm also wondering if tts agent's session mode is actually being used when spawned, or if the main agent is just sending it messages without truly establishing that persistent session context.\n\nLooking at the available tools in the main session, `sessions_spawn` can take a `cwd` parameter to set the working directory for the subagent. The subagent itself is a spawned session that can access workspace files and memory. Since tts already has session mode configured, it should retain context across interactions. The real blocker is figuring out whether the skills are being invoked as subagents or as tools—if they're tools, the exec restriction is the bottleneck; if they're subagents, I need to understand how they get spawned and what permissions they inherit.\n\nMy approach: enable `exec` in the tts agent's allowlist so skills can run their scripts, then test whether spawning the tts agent with a task actually establishes a session that can access the Selector workspace memory and use those skills properly. I need to reconsider the approach—the tts agent is spawned via `agentId`, not as a skill agent, so `sessions_spawn` with the `agentId` parameter should handle the session lifecycle correctly. The key is enabling `exec` so the skills can run their scripts, then test if the tts agent can access the necessary tools and workspace memory."},{"type":"text","text":"tts agent 的工具白名单里没有 `exec`，skills 的脚本跑不起来。先把这个放开，再测试选品 Agent 能不能正常召回记忆并使用 skill：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_r2x10rxyhxae_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/home/halei/.openclaw/agents/tts/agent/config.json","edits":[{"oldText":"\"tools\": {\n        \"allow\": [\n            \"cron\",\n            \"read\",\n            \"write\",\n            \"edit\",\n            \"apply_patch\",\n            \"memory_search\",\n            \"memory_get\",\n            \"browser\",\n            \"message\"\n        ]\n    }","newText":"\"tools\": {\n        \"allow\": [\n            \"cron\",\n            \"read\",\n            \"write\",\n            \"edit\",\n            \"apply_patch\",\n            \"memory_search\",\n            \"memory_get\",\n            \"browser\",\n            \"message\",\n            \"exec\",\n            \"web_search\",\n            \"web_fetch\"\n        ]\n    }"}]}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776161097101,"responseId":"062d4449ce5ffb43b7ceaf87852f0ac8"}}
