{"type":"message","id":"cc6818c6","parentId":"695edcc4","timestamp":"2026-04-14T10:06:05.323Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me think about what the selector agent needs to do actual product selection work:\n\n1. It has linkfox-echotik skills for TikTok product data\n2. It has 1688 skills for product sourcing\n3. It has memory of past selection work\n4. It has a SOUL.md that defines its role\n\nThe issue is: how do we actually spawn this agent and have it work? The spawn needs to use `sessions_spawn` with the right workspace and the right skills. But the spawn call itself is made by the main agent (KIIT).\n\nSo the workflow is:\n1. HALEI asks KIIT to do product selection\n\n\n2. KIIT spawns the selector agent with the Selector workspace\n3. The selector agent uses its skills and memory to do the work\n4. Results come back\n\nThe tts and product-selector configs both point to the same workspace but represent two different spawn entry points—I need to figure out which one is actually being used.\n\nLooking at the config, the product-selector uses the main agent's subagents.allowAgents setting which permits \"*\", while tts is a separate agent in the agents list that I spawn via sessions_spawn with the tts agentId. Since the openclaw.json only has entries for main and tts, the product-selector config is likely just metadata that the main agent references when spawning subagents. The key is understanding how the main agent spawns subagents and whether it uses the product-selector configuration or spawns directly with the tts agentId.\n\nWhen I spawn a subagent, I need to specify the agentId and runtime as \"acp\", and the spawned agent will use the workspace from its config. The user would typically ask me to delegate product selection work, and I'd spawn the appropriate agent to handle it. I should probably test spawning the selector agent to see if it actually works and can use the skills, but I need to be mindful that