{"type":"message","id":"79c246e3","parentId":"bbf21919","timestamp":"2026-04-14T10:11:03.546Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants the Selector workspace to have the same memory structure as the main KIIT workspace:\n- Short-term: current conversation context\n- Medium-term: memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md files\n- Long-term: MEMORY.md\n\nI need to:\n1. Create MEMORY.md in Selector workspace\n2. Create a memory/ directory if not already there\n3. The key is: memory_search tool searches both the vector DB (lancedb) AND file-based memory. The Selector workspace has its own memory files. The memory_search tool when run from the Selector context should search within that workspace's memory files.\n\nActually, looking at how memory_search works in OpenClaw - it uses the memory provider (gemini embedding) to search. \n\nBut I need to understand whether memory_search is workspace-aware or if it only searches the global index. The config shows `memorySearch: { provider: \"gemini\" }` for the main agent, which means it uses the vector database. The Selector workspace has its own memory files, but I'm not sure if memory_search queries across all workspaces or just the current one. Given that OpenClaw's memory system uses vector embeddings stored globally, I think the Selector's memory files might not be getting indexed properly unless they're in a location the global memory_search can find them.\n\nActually, the real issue is that Selector's memory files are isolated in its own directory, so memory_search probably isn't configured to look there when invoked from the Selector context. The simpler solution would be to copy or symlink the main MEMORY.md into Selector's workspace so it's included in the search results, or create a Selector-specific MEMORY.md that gets maintained alongside the main one.\n\nBut wait - there's a critical constraint here. MEMORY.md is only supposed to be loaded in the main session for security reasons, but the user wants Selector to have the same memory structure. If I let Selector read MEMORY.md directly, it would expose all the main session's private context to a subagent, which breaks the security model. I need to find a way to give Selector similar memory capabilities without compromising the isolation between sessions.\n\nThe practical solution is to create a separate `Selector/MEMORY.md` that contains only the product selection relevant information extracted from the main MEMORY.md. This way Selector gets its own long-term memory with just the data it needs, medium-term storage through daily files in the memory directory, and short-term through conversation context - maintaining the same layered structure without sharing sensitive main session content."},{"type":"text","text":"目标很清晰：给 Selector 建立完整三层记忆体系，跟主 workspace 一模一样。\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_x5w8tbhpuegv_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls ~/.openclaw/workspace/Selector/memory/"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776161440486,"responseId":"062d45a0ed6091ed32b1dd21baf11ad2"}}
